WEBVTT

00:01.084 --> 00:02.711
NARRATOR:
<i>Previously on </i> Chesapeake Shores:

00:02.794 --> 00:05.755
I'm back now. So let's just enjoy
the time we have together.

00:05.839 --> 00:06.840
[♪♪♪] Is something wrong?

00:08.007 --> 00:09.259
-I read your book.
-And?

00:09.342 --> 00:10.552
[DOOR SLAMS]

00:10.635 --> 00:12.178
-You can't publish this.
-Why?

00:12.262 --> 00:14.222
MICK:
It's your truth. Not the family's.

00:14.305 --> 00:16.933
It is what happened.
At least from what I remember.

00:17.017 --> 00:19.144
Bree, I like you,
and I don't wanna give that up.

00:19.227 --> 00:21.479
WOMAN: It looks like you have termites.
-Termites?

00:21.563 --> 00:24.065
It's a miracle
the entire house hasn't collapsed.

00:24.149 --> 00:26.234
We'd like to buy you
a new bed-and-breakfast.

00:26.317 --> 00:27.277
In Tanglewood.

00:28.236 --> 00:31.698
I asked for my old job back. Because
you were gonna give it all up for me.

00:31.781 --> 00:33.950
The least I could do was do
the same for you.

00:34.034 --> 00:38.747
I think maybe this is a chance for us
to build something different.

00:38.830 --> 00:40.040
I'm gonna go, Abby.

00:40.123 --> 00:41.249
We'll make it work.

00:41.332 --> 00:42.959
We always do, right?

00:43.042 --> 00:44.753
Every relationship takes work.

00:44.836 --> 00:49.090
-I don't know what to do.
-You have to take care of yourself first.

00:49.174 --> 00:51.885
I can't share your dreams
by giving up mine.

00:51.968 --> 00:53.511
I don't think I can do this anymore.

00:53.595 --> 00:54.596
I'm sorry.

01:02.187 --> 01:04.188
[♪♪♪]

01:07.525 --> 01:09.027
ABBY:
You brought me ice cream?

01:09.110 --> 01:11.196
KEVIN:
Well, ice cream and a question.

01:11.279 --> 01:13.698
-Ah. Nothing's ever free, is it?
-Afraid not.

01:13.782 --> 01:14.616
[ABBY CHUCKLES] Okay, so...

01:19.204 --> 01:21.915
if someone were to propose to you...

01:21.998 --> 01:23.083
"If"?

01:23.166 --> 01:25.710
Someone already did.
I used to be married, remember?

01:25.794 --> 01:28.713
Sorry, I meant, "when."
When a guy proposes to you,

01:28.797 --> 01:32.175
to you, in the future, how would
you like him to pop the question?

01:32.258 --> 01:33.885
[♪♪♪]

01:33.968 --> 01:36.596
Why? Are you thinking
about asking Sarah?!

01:36.679 --> 01:39.098
No, no, no. It's purely hypothetical.

01:39.182 --> 01:40.600
-Oh, is it?
-Yes.

01:40.683 --> 01:42.811
JESS:
What's hypothetical?

01:42.894 --> 01:46.856
Kevin is just wondering how I might like
someone to propose to me,

01:46.940 --> 01:48.942
but apparently it has nothing to do
with Sarah.

01:49.025 --> 01:51.986
-Are you gonna ask?
-No! This is just hypothetical.

01:52.070 --> 01:54.197
I just mean, like...

01:54.280 --> 01:56.991
how, when, where?

01:57.075 --> 02:00.328
If a guy were to propose,
would you like it in a forest?

02:00.411 --> 02:02.330
Or on a plane? Or would you...?

02:02.413 --> 02:05.583
Would you like it on a train?
Or would you like it in the rain?

02:05.667 --> 02:08.461
I do not like green eggs and ham.

02:08.544 --> 02:11.256
-Don't you live someplace else?
-I do. And so do you.

02:11.339 --> 02:12.382
She has a point.

02:12.465 --> 02:13.466
Why are you here?

02:13.550 --> 02:14.843
I came here to talk to Abby.

02:14.926 --> 02:16.719
Okay, if you must know my opinion,

02:16.803 --> 02:19.139
I think you can never go wrong
with tried and true:

02:19.222 --> 02:21.683
Restaurant, ring and taking a knee.

02:22.225 --> 02:23.434
[IN UNISON]
Hypothetically.

02:23.518 --> 02:28.189
Which is great,
but it's also non-hypothetically boring.

02:28.273 --> 02:29.524
So you have something better?

02:29.607 --> 02:32.152
I never really intended for this
to turn into a competition.

02:32.235 --> 02:35.822
Good, because I would win.
A proposal should be elaborate

02:35.905 --> 02:37.323
and unique and magical--

02:37.407 --> 02:40.034
Didn't you once say
that you wanted unicorns?

02:40.118 --> 02:41.286
When I was 7.

02:41.369 --> 02:44.289
And since this is hypothetical,
what's wrong with unicorns?

02:44.372 --> 02:48.585
It doesn't matter how or where you ask.
The emotions are what matter.

02:48.668 --> 02:51.546
-What matters?
-Oh, what are you doing here?

02:51.629 --> 02:55.258
-Leftovers. What are you doing here?
-Getting absolutely no help at all.

02:56.551 --> 02:59.512
I gotta go get some sleep.

02:59.596 --> 03:02.307
So that I can drive you
back to Tanglewood tomorrow.

03:03.308 --> 03:05.685
[♪♪♪]

03:06.102 --> 03:07.896
-Kevin!
-This is-- Oh, my God!

03:07.979 --> 03:08.813
What?

03:08.897 --> 03:10.648
-What? What? What?
-[ALL CHATTERING]

03:15.778 --> 03:17.030
[TRACE SIGHS]

03:17.697 --> 03:20.158
[♪♪♪]

03:20.700 --> 03:21.701
Thanks a lot.

03:23.000 --> 03:29.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

04:06.120 --> 04:07.747
[PHONE CLICKING]

04:13.920 --> 04:18.173
Hey, it's Trace again. Um...

04:18.257 --> 04:20.969
I just wanna let you know
I'm back in town.

04:21.970 --> 04:26.432
So maybe when you're not too busy,
you can give me a call back.

04:27.642 --> 04:28.476
I'm home.

04:30.687 --> 04:31.688
Bye, Abby.

04:42.865 --> 04:45.660
<i>♪ Plane ticket already paid ♪</i>

04:45.743 --> 04:48.454
<i>♪ I'm gone</i>
<i>But it don't mean nothing ♪</i>

04:48.538 --> 04:52.583
<i>♪ I'm close even though I'm far away ♪</i>

04:54.377 --> 04:57.088
<i>♪ That's how I remember you ♪</i> <i>♪ Stuck here on the red-eye special ♪</i>

04:59.966 --> 05:03.886
<i>♪ I can't wait to see you again ♪</i>

05:05.722 --> 05:09.809
<i>♪ So don't think of me</i>
<i>Not being around ♪</i>

05:11.769 --> 05:17.608
<i>♪ Just listen for the sweet, sweet sound</i>
<i>Of the taxi pulling up the driveway ♪</i>

05:17.692 --> 05:20.570
<i>♪ I'm coming home soon ♪</i>

05:23.823 --> 05:27.118
<i>♪ I'm coming home soon ♪</i>

05:27.201 --> 05:29.787
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪</i>

05:29.871 --> 05:32.957
<i>♪ Da-da-da-da ♪</i>

05:33.041 --> 05:36.169
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪</i>

05:36.252 --> 05:38.671
<i>♪ Da-da-da ♪</i>

05:38.755 --> 05:41.841
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪♪</i>

05:43.760 --> 05:45.428
[♪♪♪]

05:52.435 --> 05:54.604
KEVIN:
I think you may have overpacked.

05:54.687 --> 05:56.564
It was a long weekend.
I had to be prepared.

05:56.647 --> 05:58.149
For what? An impromptu ball?

05:58.232 --> 06:00.318
Oh, trust me, it's happened.

06:00.401 --> 06:02.528
David packed me enough snacks
for a week.

06:02.612 --> 06:03.946
You couldn't share?

06:04.030 --> 06:06.741
If Connor found out,
they'd be gone in an hour.

06:06.824 --> 06:08.284
Thanks for driving me, by the way.

06:08.367 --> 06:12.038
No problem. Sarah and I wanted
to see the place anyway...

06:12.121 --> 06:15.083
and gives us an excuse
to get away for a few days.

06:15.166 --> 06:16.000
For?

06:16.084 --> 06:17.376
"For" what?

06:17.460 --> 06:20.838
You're gonna love it.
It's perfect, and amazing, and...

06:20.922 --> 06:22.340
You keep saying that.

06:22.423 --> 06:24.050
-I do?
-Mm-hm.

06:25.468 --> 06:27.386
-Hey.
-Hey.

06:27.470 --> 06:28.638
[♪♪♪]

06:28.721 --> 06:31.390
You okay? You look nervous.

06:34.310 --> 06:37.688
No. Ahem. No, definitely not nervous.

06:37.772 --> 06:39.148
Definitely not.

06:39.232 --> 06:41.150
Great. Now you sound nervous.

06:41.234 --> 06:43.194
BREE: Hey, guys, don't leave yet.
I'm so sorry.

06:43.277 --> 06:46.489
I've been struggling with the transition
between scene 4 and 5,

06:46.572 --> 06:47.824
and the denouement...

06:47.907 --> 06:49.909
Great, another play
I'm not gonna understand.

06:50.576 --> 06:54.831
Relax, it just means "ending,"
and I think you're gonna like this one.

06:54.914 --> 06:57.542
Or you're gonna really love it. Maybe.

06:57.625 --> 07:01.546
-I forgot my coffee. So I'm gonna...
-She's writing about the family again.

07:01.629 --> 07:04.048
If she writes about the time
I got lost in the garage,

07:04.132 --> 07:05.967
I'm gonna write a play about her.

07:06.050 --> 07:07.135
I could do it.

07:07.218 --> 07:08.469
How hard could it be?

07:09.137 --> 07:10.513
[SARAH CHUCKLES]

07:11.222 --> 07:12.473
Porter Fund?

07:12.557 --> 07:14.725
Yeah, we might be taking them on
as clients.

07:14.809 --> 07:17.228
-Wow, big fish.
-Hmm.

07:17.311 --> 07:19.981
And what about, uh...?

07:20.064 --> 07:23.192
If you're wondering how I am
with Trace being back, I'm fine.

07:23.276 --> 07:26.487
No, no, I was just curious
about their stock-to-cash option.

07:26.571 --> 07:28.739
-Dad, I'm fine.
-Okay, all right.

07:28.823 --> 07:30.116
[PHONE CLICKING]

07:30.199 --> 07:32.034
[♪♪♪]

07:32.118 --> 07:33.911
Dare I ask?

07:33.995 --> 07:37.582
Hypothetically, Kevin might be
asking Sarah to marry him this weekend,

07:37.665 --> 07:40.251
and Jess is keeping us all updated.

07:40.334 --> 07:41.878
So your sister is spying?

07:41.961 --> 07:44.839
We think of it
as long-distance reconnaissance.

07:44.922 --> 07:46.841
Did you want her to add you
to the group text?

07:46.924 --> 07:49.469
No, I'll wait till they make
the announcement themselves.

07:49.552 --> 07:51.095
-Bye, Uncle Kevin.
-Bye, Aunt Jess.

07:51.179 --> 07:52.513
-Bye, hon.
-Bye, Sarah.

07:52.597 --> 07:54.056
MICK:
How about a hug for Grandpa?

07:54.140 --> 07:55.850
-Give it up.
-Bye, Grandpa.

07:55.933 --> 07:58.769
-Bye-bye.
-All right, girls, let's load up.

07:58.853 --> 08:00.980
So, uh, how is Abby doing
with Trace being back?

08:01.063 --> 08:02.690
I think she's fine with it.

08:02.773 --> 08:03.774
-Really?
-Yeah.

08:03.858 --> 08:05.776
You heard about Kevin and Sarah?

08:05.860 --> 08:08.571
Unlike everyone else,
I know when not to get involved.

08:08.654 --> 08:09.530
[HORN HONKS]

08:09.614 --> 08:10.823
Did he?

08:10.907 --> 08:12.909
[♪♪♪]

08:12.992 --> 08:15.119
Oh, that's so sweet.

08:16.454 --> 08:17.497
Aw.

08:18.915 --> 08:20.958
-Not involved, right? Oh.
-No.

08:21.709 --> 08:22.543
[DANIELLE GASPS]

08:22.627 --> 08:24.795
Do you really think
he's gonna propose this weekend?

08:24.879 --> 08:28.299
-Hypothetically.
-Then I'm hypothetically excited for them.

08:28.382 --> 08:30.635
-And for us.
-For us?

08:30.718 --> 08:33.095
I had my two-year review at the firm,

08:33.179 --> 08:37.265
and they asked what my plans were,
and I said, "Partner in five years."

08:37.683 --> 08:39.352
-And no one blinked.
-Wow!

08:39.434 --> 08:41.270
-Partnership track?
-I know, right?

08:41.354 --> 08:43.063
-Congratulations.
-Thank you.

08:43.147 --> 08:44.941
Well, I guess us should celebrate.

08:45.024 --> 08:48.819
Yeah. I was thinking
all of us NYU grads could hang out.

08:48.903 --> 08:52.782
-Haven't seen each other since the bar.
-Yeah, sounds like fun. Um...

08:52.865 --> 08:53.741
[CAR ALARM BEEPS]

08:53.824 --> 08:55.826
[♪♪♪]

08:56.869 --> 09:00.540
-You have a new car.
-I started the celebration a little early.

09:00.623 --> 09:03.584
No more breakdowns,
no more calling you to pick me up.

09:03.668 --> 09:06.546
And if you're really nice,
I might even let you drive it.

09:08.506 --> 09:10.299
-Bye.
-Bye, I'll see you later.

09:18.933 --> 09:21.477
DEL: Thank you so much
for coming in, Mr. Porter.

09:21.561 --> 09:23.854
And thank you
for considering Capital Management.

09:23.938 --> 09:26.148
First off, please, call me Derrick.

09:26.232 --> 09:28.818
And I'm looking forward
to a long relationship with you both.

09:28.901 --> 09:32.863
I'm assuming you must be the marvelous
Ms. O'Brien I keep hearing about.

09:32.947 --> 09:35.157
Just Abby. No "marvelous" needed.

09:35.241 --> 09:38.119
Uh, just before we get started,
I am going to need to access...

09:38.202 --> 09:40.746
Our proprietary financial data?
Of course.

09:40.830 --> 09:42.665
Millions of Americans trust
the Porter Fund

09:42.748 --> 09:44.375
with their retirement investments,

09:44.458 --> 09:47.878
and we have grown because
we put our trust in people like you.

09:48.254 --> 09:52.133
Considering what I know about your fund,
it will be an honor to work with you.

09:52.216 --> 09:56.971
Abby, uh, this may sound hokey,
but my father started this fund,

09:57.054 --> 09:59.724
and he believed that every family
that puts their trust in us

09:59.807 --> 10:01.392
becomes part of our family too.

10:01.934 --> 10:05.479
So on behalf of our entire family,
thank you.

10:05.563 --> 10:09.066
And if you need anything,
anything at all, please...

10:10.192 --> 10:11.193
call me personally.

10:11.277 --> 10:12.361
[♪♪♪]

10:12.445 --> 10:13.696
Shall we get started?

10:15.156 --> 10:15.990
We shall.

10:24.040 --> 10:25.458
Mom, stop reading <i>The</i> <i>Times</i>.

10:25.541 --> 10:27.960
It doesn't matter
where I am on the bestseller list.

10:28.044 --> 10:29.629
What matters is my meeting

10:29.712 --> 10:32.423
with the Kodiak Theater Group,
which starts in two minutes.

10:32.506 --> 10:34.759
According to their assistant,
they're very prompt.

10:34.842 --> 10:36.886
Ah! Oh, you moved up a spot.

10:36.969 --> 10:38.304
-What?!
-Look.

10:39.138 --> 10:40.348
[BOTH GIGGLE]

10:40.431 --> 10:43.100
I have to text Simon.
He's gonna be so proud.

10:43.184 --> 10:45.936
-So it doesn't matter, huh?
-Oh, no, it totally matters.

10:46.854 --> 10:48.648
The Kodiak Group must really want
your play

10:48.731 --> 10:50.358
if they're willing to come here.

10:50.441 --> 10:53.986
Yeah. The chances of them offering me
anything are still really slim, though.

10:54.445 --> 10:57.114
-How many other producers are there?
-Two.

10:57.198 --> 10:59.992
Okay, then don't worry.
All you need is one.

11:00.618 --> 11:02.036
[♪♪♪]

11:02.119 --> 11:04.330
Funny, Dad said the exact same thing.

11:04.413 --> 11:06.707
Yeah, we've been talking a little bit
about it.

11:06.791 --> 11:08.000
[BELLS JINGLE]

11:11.003 --> 11:12.046
Ms. O'Brien?

11:12.129 --> 11:13.714
-Oh, they are prompt.
-Yeah.

11:15.633 --> 11:18.010
Oh, I gotta-- Yeah.

11:18.094 --> 11:18.928
[SOFTLY]
Hi.

11:19.011 --> 11:21.555
[♪♪♪]

11:30.523 --> 11:31.399
JESS:
Yes!

11:32.316 --> 11:33.150
Oh!

11:33.234 --> 11:35.486
-I love you. I'm so happy.
-I love you.

11:35.569 --> 11:37.530
You bought me a rose.
Oh, I smashed it.

11:37.613 --> 11:40.241
-You bought me a rose and I smashed it.
-We can get more.

11:41.617 --> 11:43.619
You picked me a rose. Aw!

11:43.702 --> 11:46.455
Thank you. Isn't this place amazing?

11:46.539 --> 11:47.373
Just perfect.

11:48.791 --> 11:51.293
-I gotta get back. We'll talk later, okay?
-Okay.

11:51.377 --> 11:52.211
See you, guys.

11:52.294 --> 11:54.213
JESS: I love you.
DAVID: I love you.

11:54.296 --> 11:55.506
[♪♪♪]

11:55.589 --> 12:00.719
Um, yes. I'll check you guys in, in just
a second. I'll be right back, okay? Hi.

12:02.179 --> 12:03.514
Really does seem amazing.

12:03.597 --> 12:05.433
And awesome and...

12:06.892 --> 12:10.438
Actually a little bit surprised
that she said it so many times.

12:11.605 --> 12:14.608
-You got me a rose. Heh-heh.
-Yes, I did.

12:14.692 --> 12:15.526
Ah.

12:15.609 --> 12:17.319
-What?
-Just thorn.

12:18.779 --> 12:20.990
-Aw. I love you.
-I know.

12:21.073 --> 12:24.368
No. You're supposed
to say "I love you" back.

12:24.452 --> 12:27.496
Fine. Be that way.

12:27.580 --> 12:28.622
Say it.

12:28.706 --> 12:30.166
[♪♪♪]

12:30.249 --> 12:31.834
-I love you too.
-Mm.

12:39.383 --> 12:41.385
[♪♪♪]

12:59.195 --> 13:01.655
Trace. I heard you were home.

13:02.656 --> 13:06.327
-How you doing?
-I'm good. Just got in late last night.

13:07.745 --> 13:12.500
I've been trying to call Abby,
but we haven't had a chance to connect.

13:12.583 --> 13:15.169
Is she around?
I was hoping we could talk for a sec.

13:15.252 --> 13:20.424
I'm sure Abby got your message.
If she wants to talk, she'll let you know.

13:20.508 --> 13:22.510
[♪♪♪]

13:23.636 --> 13:24.470
Right.

13:25.763 --> 13:27.389
No, I get it.

13:29.391 --> 13:31.936
-Can you just make sure she gets these?
-Of course.

13:34.772 --> 13:35.731
Welcome back.

13:36.815 --> 13:37.691
Thanks, Mick.

13:47.451 --> 13:50.079
That was Trace. These are for you.

13:50.621 --> 13:53.749
I didn't know whether
you'd wanna talk to him or not.

13:53.832 --> 13:54.792
Thanks, Dad.

13:55.960 --> 13:58.045
-I'm not sure yet.
-Mm.

14:00.214 --> 14:04.343
Uh, so, ahem, how bad is it with Dilpher?

14:05.761 --> 14:09.848
He's poured the foundations
for just about every structure I've built.

14:09.932 --> 14:13.435
I got a heads-up from two city managers
there's gonna be an investigation.

14:14.979 --> 14:16.855
Seems like you can't trust anyone
these days.

14:18.732 --> 14:19.692
Derrick Porter?

14:19.775 --> 14:21.277
Yeah.

14:21.360 --> 14:23.487
His numbers are...

14:23.571 --> 14:25.072
just strange.

14:27.408 --> 14:30.035
Right now everything's
just a little confusing.

14:30.119 --> 14:31.996
[♪♪♪]

14:39.503 --> 14:43.132
SARAH: Get housekeeping and early
check-ins, tour bus is coming at 3, and...

14:43.215 --> 14:45.885
Uh, I'll get on the reservations.
We need to deal with that reunion,

14:45.968 --> 14:49.013
-and I'll start turndown service.
-I don't know how you do it.

14:49.763 --> 14:52.308
-Everything okay?
-Perfect and awesome.

14:55.394 --> 14:59.064
So do you guys have
anything special planned today?

14:59.148 --> 15:01.233
Kevin said he has plans.

15:01.317 --> 15:02.651
I do hope so.

15:02.735 --> 15:05.321
And it includes a picnic lunch
that he made,

15:05.404 --> 15:07.531
which I'm hoping doesn't kill me.

15:07.615 --> 15:09.825
David helped me put it together.

15:10.576 --> 15:12.995
Okay, David put the whole thing together.

15:13.078 --> 15:15.372
Great. Then today will be amazing.

15:15.456 --> 15:16.373
Bye.

15:16.457 --> 15:18.459
[♪♪♪]

15:26.175 --> 15:27.009
Okay.

15:27.384 --> 15:30.638
-Bree, about this play of yours...
-Mm-hm.

15:30.721 --> 15:31.847
What?

15:31.931 --> 15:35.434
Well, we've just all been
getting along lately.

15:35.517 --> 15:36.727
Mm-hm.

15:36.810 --> 15:40.230
And we've been spending
a lot of time together, which is nice, right?

15:40.314 --> 15:43.859
And it was your book that got us
all talking again, which is also very nice.

15:43.943 --> 15:45.194
Mm-hm.

15:45.277 --> 15:48.572
So, honey, we just wanna know
about your play.

15:48.656 --> 15:50.741
That's not about us too, is it?

15:50.824 --> 15:52.534
[♪♪♪]

15:55.621 --> 15:57.498
Hmm. Um...

15:58.749 --> 16:00.167
Not exactly.

16:11.303 --> 16:12.137
Hey.

16:13.806 --> 16:17.559
I, uh, hear that last storm really did
a number on your house.

16:17.643 --> 16:21.939
The house survived, but a tree decided
to take out the gazebo.

16:22.022 --> 16:25.442
That's too bad.
So how long you here for?

16:27.319 --> 16:30.572
No, I'm just curious.
I read that your tour got extended

16:30.656 --> 16:33.742
and I figured you'd only be here
a few days before flying out.

16:33.826 --> 16:34.868
Missed you too, Mick.

16:36.704 --> 16:41.250
Look, right now,
I'm just, uh, trying to fix what's broken.

16:42.543 --> 16:45.587
Yeah, but you don't see how she feels
when you're not here.

16:45.671 --> 16:48.132
Abby's my daughter, Trace, I--

16:48.215 --> 16:51.343
-I'm just looking out for her.
-I'm not leaving again.

16:51.427 --> 16:52.344
I'm here to stay.

16:53.012 --> 16:54.763
[♪♪♪]

16:54.847 --> 16:58.183
-Well, I guess we'll see.
-I guess we will.

17:00.561 --> 17:01.895
Thanks for coming by, Mick.

17:08.402 --> 17:11.864
Submitted to evidence
on January 2nd.

17:11.946 --> 17:14.950
We also have two additional reports,
one by the EPA,

17:15.034 --> 17:17.744
dated June 5th of last year--

17:17.828 --> 17:19.872
This is gonna take us
some time to review.

17:20.289 --> 17:23.041
Uh, yeah, you're right.
Okay, why don't you start with that?

17:23.125 --> 17:26.545
And then let's meet in two days
to discuss our next meeting

17:26.627 --> 17:27.921
after a cursory review.

17:28.005 --> 17:30.090
I agree. Two days.

17:32.634 --> 17:34.553
You are making us work for this.

17:34.636 --> 17:38.182
-Yeah, thank you.
-I didn't really mean it as a compliment.

17:38.265 --> 17:39.349
[PHONE BUZZES]

17:39.433 --> 17:40.309
Okay.

17:42.061 --> 17:45.147
Oh, uh, it's my brother and his girlfriend.

17:45.230 --> 17:48.317
-He's about to propose.
-And you hired a PI to take pictures?

17:50.027 --> 17:51.570
-Something like that.
-Huh.

17:51.653 --> 17:54.823
You weren't so busy trying to save
the world, I'd hire you in a second.

17:54.907 --> 17:57.159
[♪♪♪]

18:06.126 --> 18:08.045
SARAH:
I feel like Goldilocks.

18:08.128 --> 18:10.631
We hike a cliff and it's too high,

18:10.714 --> 18:13.133
we try to canoe but it starts to leak...

18:13.550 --> 18:16.011
and now we're picnicking.

18:16.095 --> 18:17.805
And it's just right?

18:18.680 --> 18:21.058
-It's pretty close.
-Yeah?

18:21.141 --> 18:21.975
[PHONE CLICKING]

18:22.059 --> 18:23.352
Okay, well...

18:23.435 --> 18:26.522
now that we're here,

18:27.189 --> 18:28.440
and it's just right,

18:28.524 --> 18:30.984
or pretty close to just right,

18:31.068 --> 18:35.781
there's been something that
I've been wanting to ask you. Oh! Oh!

18:35.864 --> 18:36.949
Oh...

18:37.032 --> 18:38.367
[♪♪♪]

18:38.450 --> 18:41.245
So much for pretty close.

18:41.328 --> 18:44.164
You know, you're not really
a picnic kind of guy.

18:44.248 --> 18:46.166
Yeah, I guess not.

18:46.250 --> 18:48.919
-It's all right, neither am I.
-Well, that's not what your dad said.

18:50.212 --> 18:51.797
You asked my dad?

18:51.880 --> 18:53.382
[♪♪♪]

18:55.008 --> 18:55.968
Uh...

18:57.344 --> 18:58.554
Kev, are you okay?

19:00.305 --> 19:05.227
I mean, you just seem disappointed
by something.

19:05.310 --> 19:09.314
And pretty close or not,
I'm having an amazing day with you.

19:10.983 --> 19:14.111
Yeah. Perfect and awesome.

19:19.783 --> 19:22.119
Not now, John.

19:22.202 --> 19:24.496
Look, if you think
you can just come down here and--

19:26.415 --> 19:28.125
It wasn't about that.

19:29.710 --> 19:34.256
It's not about the tour for me, John, okay?
It's bigger than that.

19:34.339 --> 19:36.425
I need to be here.

19:36.508 --> 19:37.968
No, I can't.

19:38.051 --> 19:39.178
[♪♪♪]

19:39.261 --> 19:42.139
Look, I'm done. I'm sorry.

19:42.222 --> 19:44.391
EMMA [SINGING]:
♪ Sometimes when the night is dark <i> </i>♪

19:44.474 --> 19:47.811
♪ And the world wants to take my heart ♪

19:47.895 --> 19:52.524
♪ And it feels like the sun
Will never shine ♪

19:55.110 --> 19:58.488
♪ I know it'll turn around ♪

19:58.572 --> 20:00.324
♪ When love-- ♪♪

20:00.407 --> 20:01.241
CHRIS:
Emma.

20:02.868 --> 20:04.536
Break ended five minutes ago.

20:05.245 --> 20:06.914
Sorry. Be right there.

20:11.084 --> 20:12.961
Trace Riley.

20:13.045 --> 20:14.963
I heard you might be around.

20:15.047 --> 20:17.674
I guess your music thing didn't work out?

20:17.758 --> 20:19.843
Everything's working out just fine.

20:20.510 --> 20:21.511
Welcome back.

20:22.721 --> 20:24.723
[♪♪♪]

20:38.320 --> 20:41.198
Emma, if you want those extra shifts,
you've got to earn it.

20:41.281 --> 20:42.991
Sorry. It won't happen again.

20:43.075 --> 20:44.326
I cannot believe you said it.

20:44.409 --> 20:46.745
Yeah. It was immediately stricken
from the record.

20:46.828 --> 20:49.373
-But I said it loud and clear.
CONNOR: Come on.

20:49.456 --> 20:50.791
"The truth?"

20:50.874 --> 20:53.794
-"You can't handle the truth!"
-"You can't handle the truth!"

20:55.587 --> 20:57.881
I am so, so jealous.

20:57.965 --> 20:59.925
I'm surprised you're not doing litigation.

21:00.008 --> 21:03.470
You spent law school talking about how
you were gonna be Clarence Darrow.

21:03.929 --> 21:06.139
DANIELLE:
Or Judge Judy.

21:06.223 --> 21:10.894
Actually, Connor is single-handedly
taking on United Metals.

21:10.978 --> 21:14.064
Well, I feel sorry for them
once you guys get to trial.

21:14.147 --> 21:15.148
Yeah, yeah.

21:15.732 --> 21:18.151
Well, we win by not going to trial, so...

21:18.277 --> 21:20.362
To billable hours.

21:20.445 --> 21:22.489
And to us taking over the world. DANIELLE: Cheers.
-Cheers.

21:24.700 --> 21:26.702
[♪♪♪] I can't believe they're shutting me down.

21:31.373 --> 21:33.375
It's wrong, Mick.

21:33.458 --> 21:35.419
We've always engineered
everything above code.

21:35.502 --> 21:37.129
So why are they going after you?

21:37.212 --> 21:38.422
I have no idea.

21:38.505 --> 21:41.091
Maybe it's an old grudge,
maybe jealousy,

21:41.174 --> 21:43.510
maybe Venus is in retrograde.

21:43.593 --> 21:45.470
-I don't know.
-This isn't a witch hunt, Paul.

21:45.554 --> 21:47.389
They must have found something.

21:47.472 --> 21:49.599
They ain't gonna find anything.

21:49.683 --> 21:51.685
Why don't you just tell me what you did?

21:54.604 --> 21:58.108
Look, Mick.
We've walked every site together.

21:58.191 --> 22:00.652
-You knew what I was doing.
-That's not an answer.

22:02.279 --> 22:05.324
Look, we're in this together.
We're partners.

22:05.407 --> 22:07.868
Are you insinuating that I knew?

22:07.951 --> 22:09.036
Knew what, Mick?

22:09.119 --> 22:13.081
Like I said before, we've always
engineered everything above code.

22:13.165 --> 22:15.959
What's your line again? That's right:

22:16.043 --> 22:17.711
It's just business.

22:17.794 --> 22:19.796
[♪♪♪]

22:24.718 --> 22:27.512
Abby. You haven't talked to him yet?

22:28.180 --> 22:31.224
No. I don't know what to say.

22:31.308 --> 22:33.393
I mean, I know what I wanna say,

22:33.477 --> 22:36.188
but when I'm standing there in front
of him, my brain gets all jumbled.

22:38.106 --> 22:40.525
So you're not getting back together, huh?

22:40.609 --> 22:42.486
I made a decision.

22:43.487 --> 22:45.739
Sounds like your mind's made up, honey.

22:47.032 --> 22:48.825
Well, doesn't mean it's easy.

22:49.618 --> 22:52.954
Okay, but I don't want somebody
who just understands my vision.

22:53.038 --> 22:55.624
-I need somebody who can hone it.
TED: I can't agree more.

22:55.707 --> 22:59.044
Okay, so for example,
the transition between scene 4 and 5...

22:59.127 --> 23:00.504
It's brilliant.

23:00.587 --> 23:01.630
[♪♪♪]

23:01.713 --> 23:04.007
Okay, uh, how about the ending?

23:04.091 --> 23:06.802
I love that part too.
It's my favorite part of your play.

23:06.885 --> 23:10.972
Okay, thank you so much, Mr. Steiff.

23:11.056 --> 23:14.684
I'm gonna think about your proposal.
In the meantime, I do have to...

23:14.768 --> 23:16.561
-You know.
-Oh, right, you're closing.

23:16.645 --> 23:19.189
So sorry.
I'm just such a huge fan, and I...

23:19.272 --> 23:21.316
Thank you, thank you,
thank you so much.

23:21.399 --> 23:22.359
-Bye.
-Okay, bye.

23:22.442 --> 23:23.276
-Bye.
-Bye.

23:23.360 --> 23:24.945
[MEGAN CHUCKLES]

23:25.028 --> 23:28.031
Oh, he seems very friendly.

23:28.115 --> 23:31.368
Teddy Steiff is a fluffy pillow.
Too soft to hold shape.

23:31.451 --> 23:33.954
I just want somebody I can trust.

23:34.037 --> 23:37.040
-Yes.
-Thanks for watching the store, Mom.

23:37.124 --> 23:41.795
No problem. Gave me a nice little break
from the mayor and his opinions on art.

23:45.006 --> 23:46.091
So my play...

23:47.217 --> 23:48.176
Mm.

23:48.927 --> 23:50.053
[BREE CHUCKLES]

23:50.137 --> 23:51.888
...is not about the family.

23:51.972 --> 23:55.142
Oh. Bree. Thank you.

23:56.143 --> 23:57.310
-Really?
-Mm-hm.

24:02.357 --> 24:05.652
<i>"Hummingbirds in the Attic,</i>
by Bree O'Brien."

24:05.735 --> 24:07.946
Yup. It's about a, uh, bookstore owner

24:08.029 --> 24:11.283
who is trying to find her voice as a writer

24:11.366 --> 24:14.452
while dating a British author.

24:15.453 --> 24:18.123
So, basically, it's about you and Simon.

24:18.623 --> 24:21.126
No, definitely me and Simon.

24:21.209 --> 24:22.127
Okay.

24:24.504 --> 24:25.547
I can't wait.

24:28.592 --> 24:31.428
It's a lot harder to get engaged
than I thought.

24:31.511 --> 24:32.512
Hypothetically.

24:33.638 --> 24:34.931
Yeah.

24:35.015 --> 24:37.809
You know,
Georgia and I never really got engaged.

24:38.185 --> 24:40.645
Just sort of happened.

24:41.897 --> 24:44.900
This time I want it to be different.
I want it to be perfect.

24:46.860 --> 24:48.445
There's no such thing.

24:48.528 --> 24:50.697
You and David seem to be
in perfect sync.

24:50.780 --> 24:52.282
Yeah, well, not here.

24:54.701 --> 24:56.161
I hate it here.

24:57.245 --> 25:00.582
Everywhere I turn, I see David's parents.
And not in a good way.

25:01.541 --> 25:04.294
Well, because there isn't a good way.

25:04.377 --> 25:08.089
It's just, this place will never be ours.

25:08.173 --> 25:11.509
It's a job, not a family.

25:11.593 --> 25:15.513
-Have you talked to David about it?
-No. I don't think I can.

25:15.597 --> 25:19.684
He's just so happy. How can I ask him
to give up his dream?

25:21.728 --> 25:25.398
But you and Sarah,
you gotta make that work.

25:25.482 --> 25:27.150
[♪♪♪]

25:27.234 --> 25:31.154
It's right, Kev. You love her, we love her.

25:32.364 --> 25:35.450
Perfect or not, just ask.

25:36.576 --> 25:37.410
SARAH:
Hey.

25:38.328 --> 25:39.871
-Hey.
-Hey.

25:39.955 --> 25:41.915
-You making s'mores?
-Yeah.

25:42.999 --> 25:44.501
Would you like one? Yes, please.

25:46.169 --> 25:48.546
[ACOUSTIC GUITAR PLAYING]

25:48.630 --> 25:53.134
TRACE [SINGING]: ♪ Crazy dreams
Pull me further from you ♪

25:53.218 --> 25:56.221
♪ These places and faces ♪

25:56.304 --> 26:00.141
♪ But I'm still alone in this town ♪

26:00.225 --> 26:04.187
♪ Nothing matters the way you do ♪♪

26:04.271 --> 26:05.105
Hey. Connor.

26:07.816 --> 26:09.401
What are you still doing here?

26:09.484 --> 26:11.861
Saying goodbye to my friends out front,
saw your truck.

26:11.945 --> 26:13.905
It's good to have you back. How was it?

26:14.698 --> 26:16.574
It was, uh...

26:16.658 --> 26:17.826
It was good.

26:19.202 --> 26:21.037
-I bet.
-It was good.

26:21.121 --> 26:22.914
You, uh, writing something new?

26:24.374 --> 26:26.209
Maybe, I don't know.

26:26.293 --> 26:28.503
How about you? How's the family?

26:28.586 --> 26:30.839
Oh, they're all good.

26:30.922 --> 26:32.841
I mean, nothing really changes here.

26:33.675 --> 26:36.094
Trust me, that's not such a bad thing.

26:36.177 --> 26:39.472
That's easy for you to say.
You've been everywhere.

26:39.556 --> 26:42.475
Yeah. When I should've
just stayed right here.

26:45.645 --> 26:47.939
Have you talked to Abby yet?

26:49.024 --> 26:50.233
I've tried.

26:53.778 --> 26:57.741
Well, I don't know
if you're still much of a runner,

26:57.824 --> 27:01.202
but I hear Remmey Beach is nice.

27:01.286 --> 27:02.454
[♪♪♪]

27:02.537 --> 27:03.455
Around 7 a.m.

27:09.294 --> 27:10.462
Thanks, Connor.

27:10.545 --> 27:11.546
No problem.

27:16.468 --> 27:17.719
[♪♪♪]

27:17.802 --> 27:21.556
So when I told you that I wanted
to come here with Jess,

27:22.599 --> 27:25.393
I wasn't being entirely honest with you.

27:25.477 --> 27:26.311
Eggplant.

27:27.604 --> 27:28.980
What?

27:29.064 --> 27:32.067
I haven't been entirely honest
with you either.

27:33.068 --> 27:37.697
When we both grabbed that eggplant
at the farmer's market, I did it on purpose.

27:37.781 --> 27:39.282
So you stole the eggplant from me?

27:39.366 --> 27:41.534
Well, I mean, you were mildly cute.

27:41.618 --> 27:44.412
And I figured it would give us
something to talk about.

27:44.496 --> 27:47.123
You're telling me this now, why?

27:47.207 --> 27:50.001
Because I don't want there
to be any secrets between us.

27:50.085 --> 27:52.754
And I love you.

27:52.837 --> 27:55.215
-And I love that we're here--
-Okay, before we go on...

27:55.298 --> 27:56.174
"mildly cute"?

27:56.257 --> 27:57.092
[♪♪♪]

27:57.717 --> 27:59.260
Yeah. Mildly.

28:07.310 --> 28:09.562
Listen. Sarah.

28:11.314 --> 28:12.649
I love you,

28:12.732 --> 28:17.529
and the real reason
why I wanted to come here...

28:17.612 --> 28:19.114
[DISHES CLATTERING]

28:19.197 --> 28:22.367
WOMAN: I was just trying to get through.
Are you okay?

28:22.450 --> 28:25.203
Okay, we're gonna remake everything.
Call in the night staff,

28:25.286 --> 28:27.455
-tell them it's an emergency.
-I'm on it.

28:27.539 --> 28:28.623
You okay, David?

28:29.416 --> 28:31.459
Yeah. Um...

28:34.254 --> 28:36.798
No. No. Not even close.

28:38.049 --> 28:41.553
But don't tell Jess.
I don't wanna ruin this for her.

28:42.595 --> 28:44.597
[♪♪♪]

28:52.397 --> 28:54.274
MEGAN: Hey.
-Hey.

28:54.357 --> 28:56.943
I got Carrie and Caitlyn
some new leotards.

28:57.026 --> 28:59.738
Oh, great. They're still at practice.
They'll be home any minute.

29:01.239 --> 29:02.365
Are you still working?

29:02.449 --> 29:03.366
Oh, yeah.

29:03.450 --> 29:05.452
Well, you want some good news?

29:05.535 --> 29:07.120
I read Bree's play.

29:07.203 --> 29:09.497
And it's not about the family this time.

29:09.581 --> 29:11.416
Oh, well, that's a relief.

29:11.499 --> 29:12.459
[♪♪♪]

29:12.542 --> 29:15.211
Although when she told me
it had a "happily ever after" ending,

29:15.295 --> 29:16.296
I figured as much.

29:16.379 --> 29:19.132
What? You don't think it's possible?

29:19.215 --> 29:22.677
No, I think it's possible,
I just think the O'Briens are complicated.

29:24.471 --> 29:27.348
Well, it's gonna get complicated for Bree.

29:27.432 --> 29:29.642
She said
she wrote it about her and Simon.

29:30.685 --> 29:31.853
Let me know what you think.

29:36.149 --> 29:38.777
Ah, so do you think
he's gonna propose soon or what?

29:38.860 --> 29:42.697
Well, I hope so, or else we've all wasted
a lot of screen time on him.

29:42.781 --> 29:43.948
BREE: Mm-hm.
ABBY: Kevin...

29:44.032 --> 29:48.828
Well, it is always nice when the author
is standing next to a picture of the author.

29:48.912 --> 29:49.788
I know you.

29:50.330 --> 29:51.998
You're Hannah Urso.

29:52.081 --> 29:55.752
I saw your last play
at the National Theatre in D.C.

29:55.835 --> 29:56.795
It was amazing.

29:56.878 --> 29:59.088
This is my sister, Abby.
Abby, this is Hannah Urso.

29:59.172 --> 30:01.299
-Nice to meet you.
-Nice to meet you.

30:01.382 --> 30:04.803
I'm actually going to, uh, Sally's.
Can I get either of you anything?

30:04.886 --> 30:06.137
I'm good. Thank you.

30:06.221 --> 30:07.764
-Okay, bye.
-Bye-bye.

30:07.847 --> 30:09.682
So, um, what are you--?

30:09.766 --> 30:12.894
I just signed on as the resident director
at the Baltimore Rep,

30:12.977 --> 30:14.729
and I wanted to see you personally.

30:14.813 --> 30:15.897
You're at the Rep?

30:15.980 --> 30:19.150
And I wanna direct your play.

30:19.234 --> 30:20.527
[♪♪♪]

30:22.237 --> 30:23.863
Cool.

30:23.947 --> 30:25.740
Ahem. Cool.

30:25.824 --> 30:27.116
Yeah. Um...

30:27.200 --> 30:29.202
Well, we should talk.

30:29.285 --> 30:30.537
We could do that,

30:30.620 --> 30:34.249
and I could pitch you on how well
I think we'd work together,

30:34.332 --> 30:37.752
or I could give you
some of my thoughts.

30:37.836 --> 30:39.671
And then you could let me know...

30:39.754 --> 30:41.548
-If we're a good fit?
-Yeah.

30:41.631 --> 30:43.258
-I like that.
-Mm-hm.

30:43.341 --> 30:45.093
Okay, so...

30:46.386 --> 30:48.179
A couple of bumps.

30:48.263 --> 30:51.641
-Your transition between scenes 4 and 5.
-Oh.

30:51.724 --> 30:52.934
It doesn't work.

30:53.017 --> 30:54.894
I just--
There's tonal differences between--

30:54.978 --> 30:58.731
Jace's angst and Melanie's, uh,
desire for acceptance.

30:58.815 --> 31:00.525
-Yes.
-Mm-hm.

31:00.608 --> 31:03.945
And I'm just not sure I understand

31:04.028 --> 31:06.739
what Melanie really wants
in a relationship.

31:06.823 --> 31:07.782
Neither do I.

31:08.992 --> 31:10.034
-Yes.
-Let's get to work.

31:10.118 --> 31:11.828
-Mm-hm. Mm-hm.
-Mm-hm.

31:12.787 --> 31:15.874
Well, at least Bree is getting
what she wants.

31:17.584 --> 31:19.127
Aren't you?

31:19.210 --> 31:20.712
I don't know.

31:20.795 --> 31:22.171
I thought so.

31:22.255 --> 31:26.593
But I became an environmental lawyer
because Uncle Thomas offered me a job

31:26.676 --> 31:28.678
when no one else would.

31:28.761 --> 31:33.474
And for the past two years, I've just been
saying yes to people and to jobs,

31:33.558 --> 31:36.561
and lately, I've been thinking
if I'd stuck it out

31:36.644 --> 31:38.062
and stayed in the corporate world...

31:39.188 --> 31:40.398
what might have been?

31:40.481 --> 31:44.402
That's funny because I've been
thinking I should've gotten out.

31:44.485 --> 31:46.654
Hey, have you heard
of the Porter Fund?

31:46.738 --> 31:47.572
Yeah.

31:49.157 --> 31:52.201
Okay, so they're paying out dividends

31:52.285 --> 31:54.996
based on earnings
that only seem like they're coming

31:55.079 --> 31:56.831
from bringing in new investors.

31:56.915 --> 31:58.917
-Ponzi scheme.
-Yeah.

32:00.668 --> 32:05.548
I don't know. But I will deal with it,
just like I deal with everything else.

32:05.632 --> 32:07.592
[♪♪♪]

32:07.675 --> 32:09.177
Like you and Trace?

32:09.260 --> 32:10.595
Yeah, I guess.

32:11.888 --> 32:17.143
Lately I just feel like I need to go back
to who I used to be for a little while.

32:17.226 --> 32:19.812
Yeah, sometimes I wanna go back
to the old me too...

32:20.980 --> 32:22.398
but I left him in Baltimore.

32:24.359 --> 32:25.818
Well, you should look him up.

32:28.237 --> 32:29.113
CONNOR:
Hm.

32:31.491 --> 32:33.451
You didn't say anything, did you?

32:33.534 --> 32:35.870
No, but you probably should.

32:36.913 --> 32:38.539
You think so?

32:38.623 --> 32:39.999
Worth a try.

32:40.083 --> 32:41.209
I guess.

32:41.292 --> 32:43.711
-Well, thank you for coming.
-Yeah, thanks for having us.

32:45.713 --> 32:48.007
Well, I am sorry to see you go.

32:48.091 --> 32:49.509
Me too.

32:49.592 --> 32:52.261
Kevin, there's no such thing as perfect.

32:52.345 --> 32:55.515
And you don't need perfect
because you have each other.

32:57.058 --> 32:59.686
So do you. Tell David how you feel.

33:01.312 --> 33:03.272
Like, for real?

33:03.356 --> 33:05.024
Yeah, like, for real.

33:05.692 --> 33:07.151
It'll be okay, Jess.

33:08.861 --> 33:10.905
Okay, picture for the road.

33:10.989 --> 33:12.740
What, you haven't got enough already?

33:12.824 --> 33:13.700
What?

33:13.783 --> 33:15.660
I love you, Jess, but you're a horrible spy.

33:15.743 --> 33:17.161
[♪♪♪]

33:17.245 --> 33:18.329
Pfft.

33:19.330 --> 33:20.832
I don't know what you're talking about.

33:20.915 --> 33:21.791
[CAMERA CLICKS]

33:22.750 --> 33:24.502
-Bye.
-Bye.

33:28.214 --> 33:29.590
Drive safe.

33:31.426 --> 33:33.428
[PLAYING COUNTRY MUSIC]

33:39.183 --> 33:41.310
You look like you could use a drink.

33:41.394 --> 33:42.895
How can you tell?

33:42.979 --> 33:45.732
Because otherwise,
this music is unbearable.

33:45.815 --> 33:46.941
I'll take a beer.

33:50.028 --> 33:51.487
I liked your song.

33:53.197 --> 33:56.242
So embarrassing.
I never sing for anybody.

33:56.325 --> 33:57.201
Why not?

33:57.910 --> 34:01.414
You sing from the heart.
That's not always easy.

34:01.497 --> 34:03.666
You don't seem to have
any trouble with that.

34:03.750 --> 34:06.294
For me, writing from the heart's
the easy part.

34:06.377 --> 34:08.504
Following it is a whole different thing.

34:08.588 --> 34:11.424
Story of my life too. Emma Rogers. Trace. So you're a singer-songwriter?

34:14.927 --> 34:18.264
Server-songwriter.
Like I said, I don't sing for people.

34:19.056 --> 34:22.435
Maybe you should. Especially this song.

34:23.351 --> 34:25.897
Yeah, well, don't count on it.

34:30.818 --> 34:32.945
[♪♪♪]

34:33.029 --> 34:36.239
Okay. So here's the deal.

34:36.324 --> 34:39.494
I love you, a lot,
but you already know that,

34:39.577 --> 34:42.163
and I'm just saying it
because I like saying it. A lot.

34:42.246 --> 34:45.333
I do too, but there's something else
that we should talk about.

34:45.416 --> 34:47.877
How we love each other.
That's not what I wanna talk about.

34:47.960 --> 34:50.670
I wanna talk about being miserable.

34:50.755 --> 34:53.216
Because I am miserable. I hate it here.

34:53.299 --> 34:54.175
I do too.

34:54.257 --> 34:56.969
It reminds me of your parents
and being in your parents' house,

34:57.053 --> 34:58.638
which is unfair.

34:58.721 --> 35:00.890
No, no, Jess, I'm agreeing with you.

35:00.973 --> 35:02.600
-You are?
-Yes.

35:02.683 --> 35:04.143
Completely.

35:04.227 --> 35:07.939
Oh. Okay, then. I'm gonna skip ahead.

35:08.815 --> 35:11.651
Um, I think we should go back
to Chesapeake Shores

35:11.734 --> 35:13.027
and try to rebuild our inn,

35:13.111 --> 35:16.781
because it's ours and it's our home
and we built it and--

35:18.950 --> 35:20.827
-I think it's a great idea.
-Really?

35:20.910 --> 35:22.495
-Yeah.
-Thank you. I'm...

35:22.578 --> 35:26.415
-Heh-heh. Thank you.
-I know. I know.

35:26.499 --> 35:28.501
[♪♪♪]

35:33.214 --> 35:35.800
I'm gonna need to know
how much exposure I'm gonna have.

35:36.843 --> 35:38.261
All right, well, you co--

35:38.344 --> 35:40.847
Okay, good, thank you. Appreciate it.

35:42.932 --> 35:44.058
-Hey.
-Hey.

35:46.185 --> 35:48.479
So here's what I find amazing.

35:48.563 --> 35:51.774
For two hours, Carrie and Caitlyn
have been doing backflips,

35:51.858 --> 35:54.569
and they still have energy
to run up the stairs and do homework.

35:54.652 --> 35:56.571
I threw my knee out just watching them.

35:56.654 --> 35:58.281
Is this for my knee?

35:58.364 --> 36:00.199
Stomach, knee, take your pick.

36:01.993 --> 36:06.706
Oh, boy. I'm beginning to get
why the kids love this so much.

36:06.789 --> 36:08.082
Hm. Mm-hm.

36:08.833 --> 36:12.003
I don't know if you remember,
but they got this from us.

36:12.086 --> 36:13.045
That's right.

36:14.672 --> 36:15.882
Sunday night sundaes.

36:15.965 --> 36:17.300
Mm-hm.

36:17.383 --> 36:18.759
That was nice.

36:18.843 --> 36:20.428
Yes, it was.

36:20.511 --> 36:22.388
[♪♪♪]

36:31.522 --> 36:32.481
Um...

36:33.107 --> 36:38.446
Connor, we need you to formally accept
our timeline for review.

36:38.529 --> 36:41.032
Yeah, so we can meet again
in two months?

36:41.115 --> 36:42.283
Maybe three.

36:43.826 --> 36:45.786
Yeah, and what about after that?

36:45.870 --> 36:46.746
Excuse me?

36:47.914 --> 36:49.040
Thing is...

36:49.123 --> 36:51.125
[♪♪♪]

36:52.543 --> 36:53.878
I can win this.

36:54.587 --> 36:56.589
I'm sorry. What did you just say?

36:58.466 --> 37:01.719
I immediately move to take this to court
at the earliest possible date.

37:03.888 --> 37:06.557
I thought we were going to continue
the discovery process.

37:06.641 --> 37:07.642
Not anymore.

37:14.106 --> 37:17.026
I have never seen anyone take longer
to fix a flat.

37:17.109 --> 37:18.736
Maybe if we didn't take the scenic route.

37:20.488 --> 37:22.031
Kev, you gotta see this.

37:22.114 --> 37:24.116
[♪♪♪]

37:49.934 --> 37:50.768
Sarah.

37:54.355 --> 37:57.108
I love you more than anything.

38:05.074 --> 38:10.288
<i>♪ Oh ♪</i>

38:11.038 --> 38:13.708
<i>♪ But it seems ♪</i>

38:14.208 --> 38:15.334
Will you marry me?

38:19.714 --> 38:21.340
Kevin O'Brien...

38:23.718 --> 38:24.760
I love you.

38:25.594 --> 38:30.808
<i>♪ I don't care where the hours go ♪</i>

38:33.769 --> 38:35.479
You're supposed
to say "I love you" back.

38:36.230 --> 38:38.024
Fine, be that way.

38:39.734 --> 38:41.986
I will love you forever.

38:43.279 --> 38:46.574
<i>♪ As long as I have you ♪</i>

38:46.657 --> 38:47.700
So?

38:49.368 --> 38:50.494
-Yes.
-Yeah?

38:50.578 --> 38:51.579
[KEVIN CHUCKLES]

38:55.666 --> 38:57.376
Oh. Here.

39:01.172 --> 39:06.635
<i>♪ And I don't care if we never know ♪</i>

39:08.429 --> 39:13.934
<i>♪ I will stand with you on our own ♪</i>

39:15.519 --> 39:22.193
<i>♪ As long as I have you I'm home ♪♪</i>

39:26.655 --> 39:27.490
ABBY:
Trace?

39:29.909 --> 39:31.369
Abby, hey.

39:31.452 --> 39:34.038
Yeah, the, um...

39:34.121 --> 39:36.791
The flowers were beautiful, thank you.

39:36.874 --> 39:40.127
I'm so sorry that I haven't had a chance
to return your call. I just...

39:40.211 --> 39:42.421
No, no, I get it.

39:42.505 --> 39:43.756
I've been busy too.

39:44.632 --> 39:45.466
I...

39:46.550 --> 39:48.219
Wow, it's, uh...

39:49.762 --> 39:51.222
It's good to see you.

39:52.390 --> 39:53.432
Yeah, you too.

39:56.602 --> 39:58.771
So you're back.

39:58.854 --> 40:04.360
Yeah. Yeah, the label wanted
to extend the tour, but I was done.

40:04.860 --> 40:08.489
I'm so happy you followed your dreams.

40:08.572 --> 40:11.492
-I want you to have it all.
-Yeah, I know.

40:13.494 --> 40:17.915
But what if...?
What if I don't want that anymore?

40:19.250 --> 40:24.004
Trace, please don't.
I can't go on that roller coaster again.

40:24.088 --> 40:28.884
We just keep doing the same thing,
and I can't live my life like that.

40:28.968 --> 40:31.929
And I don't want to either,
which is why I came home.

40:33.097 --> 40:34.890
You didn't have to. I didn't ask you to.

40:34.974 --> 40:38.185
I know. I know, and I love you for that.

40:39.186 --> 40:40.604
But I'm here to stay.

40:41.689 --> 40:43.023
It'll be different this time.

40:43.107 --> 40:46.735
Yeah, but we keep just having
the same conversation.

40:46.819 --> 40:49.238
And every time we do this,
it just hurts more.

40:49.321 --> 40:51.949
And I can't hurt any more
than I already have, so...

40:52.032 --> 40:53.117
Abby.

40:53.200 --> 40:55.035
I never meant to hurt you.

40:57.913 --> 40:58.747
I know.

41:01.083 --> 41:02.251
But I can't go back.

41:04.879 --> 41:05.880
And neither should you.

41:05.963 --> 41:07.965
[♪♪♪] [♪♪♪]

